The Guild of Medical Directors (GMD) has disclosed that all patients admitted to private hospitals in Nigeria will be declared COVID-19 positive until proven otherwise via appropriate testing procedures. A statement signed by its president, Professor Femi Babalola yesterday in Abuja said that the decision on patients COVID-19 status was taken after its doctors which represents private medical practitioners in the nation were exposed to the virus by patients who had not disclosed their travel histories. Babalola said the impression created that the guild members would knowingly treat infected patients in their facilities for financial reward was erroneous. Consequently, Babalola said the guild in previous meetings with the Ministry of Health, stressed that they are in the frontline of the battle against the COVID-19 epidemic, and will act in line with globally acceptable standards. He lamented that three of the guild’s members had died after coming into contact with infected patients. He, however, asked the Ministry of Health to assist private hospitals with protective equipment as they were not only dealing with the COVID-19 crisis but had other illnesses they needed to attend to. The statement reads in part: “The impression that private hospitals in Nigeria are keen to treat patients with COVID-19 infection, perhaps for monetary gain, must be dispelled. “Permit me to mention that three of our colleagues have already died including the proprietor of Daura Clinics and Medical Centre in Katsina State, Dr. Aliyu Yakubu, Dr Dominic Essien of San Dominic Hospital in Uyo, Akwa Ibom State and a well-renowned obstetrician who died recently in Lagos, Dr. Emeka Chugbo. “The death of Dr. Chugbo is perhaps illustrative of the dilemma faced by private practitioners in Nigeria.’’ He said to facilitate the quick identification of patients with COVID 19, private hospitals need to be provided with rapid serological test kits. 